<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<Data CreatedBy="admin" CreatedOn="634128265651632031" UpdatedBy="admin" UpdatedOn="634128266687888663">
  <Properties />
  <Nodes>
    <Header Code="HeaderElement1" Type="Subtitle" ShowInTOC="0"><![CDATA[The example]]></Header>
    <Paragraph Code="ParagraphElement1"><![CDATA[<p>The demonstrated <em>ToolBar </em>contains three <em>Buttons </em>with <em>Pushed</em>, <em>Toggle </em>and <em>DropDown </em>styles. Click on the 'Push' button the message 'Pushed button has been clicked!' will be shown. Click on the 'Toggle' Button the message 'Toggle button is turn on!' will be shown and the Button will be still pushed. After the next click the Button is switched to normal state.  Click on the 'DropDown' button, the DropDown menu will be shown.</p>]]></Paragraph>
    <Header Code="HeaderElement2" Type="Subtitle" ShowInTOC="0"><![CDATA[General Info]]></Header>
    <Paragraph Code="ParagraphElement2"><![CDATA[<p>The <em>Button </em>of the Visual WebGui <em>ToolBar </em>contains <em>Style </em>property that defines its style. The button can be the following styles:<br /><strong>PushButton </strong>- a standard, three-dimensional button.<br /><strong>ToggleButton </strong>-a toggle button that appears sunken when clicked and retains the sunken appearance until clicked again.<br /><strong>Separator </strong>- a space or line between toolbar buttons. The appearance depends on the value of the <em>Appearance</em> property.<br /><strong>DropDownButton </strong>- a drop-down control that displays a menu or other window when clicked.</p>]]></Paragraph>
  </Nodes>
</Data>
